properties.headline: Hydrologic Outlook issued January 9 at 11:14AM CST by NWS Lincoln IL
properties.description:
This hydrologic outlook includes the following river in Illinois:

Illinois River...

The following river information is based on future predicted
rainfall. The exact amount, intensity, timing, and location of the
rain that will occur is still uncertain. These outlook stages are
provided to show what may be expected if the forecast precipitation
occurs. Once there is more certainty about the river forecasts, a
flood warning or statement will be issued if the threat materializes.

For the Illinois River at Henry...the latest stage is 16.4 feet at 11
AM Thursday. Flood stage is 23.0 feet. Moderate flooding is
forecast...with a crest of 27.7 feet Thursday morning...which is 4.7
feet above flood stage. The river should rise above the flood stage
of 23.0 feet Monday afternoon. At 28.0 feet...Flooding begins to
affect buildings east of Illinois Route 29 in Sparland.

For the Illinois River at Peoria...the latest stage is 12.0 feet at
11 AM Thursday. Flood stage is 18.0 feet. Moderate flooding is
forecast...with a crest of 23.4 feet Thursday morning...which is 5.4
feet above flood stage. The river should rise above the flood stage
of 18.0 feet Monday evening. At 23.0 feet...Some secondary roads
affected in Peoria county and damage begins to buildings in Rome.

For the Illinois River near Havana...the latest stage is 12.3 feet at
11 AM Thursday. Flood stage is 14.0 feet. Moderate flooding is
forecast...with a crest of 19.2 feet Thursday morning...which is 5.2
feet above flood stage. The river should rise above the flood stage
of 14.0 feet Sunday evening. At 14.0 feet...Minor flooding begins to
agricultural areas not protected by levees.

For the Illinois River at Beardstown...the latest stage is 12.0 feet
at 11 AM Thursday. Flood stage is 14.0 feet. Moderate flooding is
forecast...with a crest of 19.0 feet Thursday morning...which is 5.0
feet above flood stage. The river should rise above the flood stage
of 14.0 feet Sunday evening. At 12.0 feet...Pumping begins in
drainage and levee districts protecting about 59000 acres.
